*User Story:*

As a recruiter, I want to be able to expand the sliding side panel wider, so that I can see emails in their longer form factor

*Context:*

The sliding side panel should be updated to allow the possibility of it to grow in size.

 
h2. Scenarios:

{color:#4c9aff}*Scenario 1 - Side Panel should expand further and add drop shadow if expand/grow event is dispatched - L, XL, XXL screens (i.e. L size and larger)*{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Given:* the side panel exists{color}

{color:#172b4d}*And* the user's screen resolution is L or XL{color}

{color:#172b4d}*When:* an event is dispatched to grow/expand the panel{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Then:* the panel can expand up to 1000px per the figma and a shadow appears on the rest of the page behind the panel{color}

 

{color:#4c9aff}*Scenario 2 - Side Panel should expand further and add drop shadow if expand/grow event is dispatched - M, S screens (i.e. smaller than L size)*{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Given:* the side panel exists{color}

{color:#172b4d}*And* the user's screen resolution is M or S {color}

{color:#172b4d}*When:* an event is dispatched to grow/expand the panel{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Then:* the panel can expand up to 800px per the figma and a shadow appears on the rest of the page behind the panel{color}

 

{color:#4c9aff}*Scenario 3 - Responsiveness - XXL screen for pushed content & overlay*{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Given:* the side panel exists {color}

{color:#172b4d}*And* the user's screen resolution is XL (the main content is pushed){color}

{color:#172b4d}*When:* an event is dispatched to grow/expand the panel and the panel grows{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Then:* the content on the rest of the page is overlayed{color}

 

{color:#4c9aff}*Scenario 4 - Closing & reopening the panel*{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Given:* the side panel is open and is in a grow state{color}

{color:#172b4d}*When:* the toggle button is clicked to close the panel {color}

{color:#172b4d}*And* then clicked again to reopen the panel{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Then:* the side panel is {color}{color:#ff8b00}??? (should it reopen as grown or go back to the initial size) - use case to consider I am writing a email, but in the middle of that i need to check an info, so i close it check what i need and then return to what it was{color}

 

{color:#4c9aff}*Scenario 5 - Switching between tasks*{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Given:* the side panel is open and is in a grow state{color}

{color:#172b4d}*When:* a task button is clicked to switch the selected task{color}

{color:#172b4d}*Then:* the side panel shrinks back to its regular open size{color}

 

*Milestone Test:*
 *  Check My Tasks/ Inbox to ensure it works correctly there, as the candidate profile can be opened there

 

*Question & Answer:*
 * {color:#172b4d}Do we need to consider smaller screens for the 900px growth? Should this be more dynamic & be percentage of the screen width rather than static 900px? Can it take up more of the screen? Should the content on the rest of the page be pushed/overlayed on grow? - let's check with UX on this  - UX confirmed 1000px and 800px, and XL behaviour{color}

 

*{color:#172b4d}Dev notes:{color}*
 * {color:#172b4d}Do we want another event for "shrink" or should subsequent grow events re-shrink?{color}
 ** {color:#172b4d}chatted with Igor on this and initial thoughts are that having 2 events might be better. It gives more control to the messaging code to decide whether the panel should grow or shrink compared to if the panel controlled the behaviour by listening for subsequent events. 2 events allow for more explicit control over the behaviour, i.e. we know for certain that dispatching a shrink event will always shrink the panel and dispatching a grow event will always grow the panel rather than dispatching a single event and potentially not knowing if this will cause a shrink or grow{color}
 * {color:#172b4d}Screen size breakpoints are from canvas [https://canvas.workdaydesign.com/get-started/for-developers/guides/responsive-styling#canvas-breakpoints]:{color}
 ** {{{}zero{}}}: styles applied from {{0px}} up until (but not including) {{320px}}
 ** {{{}s{}}}: styles applied from {{320px}} up until (but not including) {{768px}}
 ** {{{}m{}}}: styles applied from {{768px}} up until (but not including) {{1024px}}
 ** {{{}l{}}}: styles applied from {{1024px}} up until (but not including) {{1440px}}
 ** {{{}xl{}}}: styles applied from {{1440px}} and up
 ** Note: xxl is not in canvas but we can treat it as 1920px as we use this in SSP today
